the three young cops did a doubletake when they 
spotted the citys mostarrested burglar sitting in the back room 
of chicago joes but there was nothing to worry about 
joseph pops panczko a 12time loser with more than 150 
arrests under his belt was in good hands the plainclothes 
detectives and the fbi agent were chipping in for his shrimp 
dinner and the advertising executive was plying him with shots and 
beer 
it was the monthly meeting of the merry gangsters and panczko 
a frequent guest of the state was the guest of honor 
despite their fearsome name the gangsters are just a group of 
otherwise reputable citizens who take pride in chicagos sordid 
past 
we just sit around and talk said retired adman billy 
reilly who founded the group with friends richard lindberg and 
nathan kaplan a year and a half ago 
much of the talk is about mobsters and madams but honor is also 
paid to corrupt cops and greedy politicians 
you can never get tired of this city its got real people in 
it real characters said kaplan 69 a freelance writer and 
retired salesman i go to other cities and watch the news i see 
their city councils theyve got straight bellies and good posture 
they use good diction i dont feel like im with real people 
by kaplans definition panczko 72 is a real person complete 
with potbelly 
despite his 50plus years as a professional criminal he was 
greeted affectionately tuesday night by the gangster regulars 
including burt neilson and jim brindisi both retired detectives 
panczko also got a special hello from a newcomer fbi agent bill 
clancy 
ive heard a lot about you pops but dont worry im a 
specialist in whitecollar crime clancy said 
theres nothing white collar about panczko who got his nickname 
from the only legitimate job he ever tried driving a softdrink 
truck 
i hated them calling me hey pop man so i went back to 
stealing he said 
i started stealing chickens when i was 11 and got my first 
pinch for swiping some of those dago cheeses you grind up and put 
on spaghetti said panczko if it wasnt wired down i stole it 
or maybe my brothers did one time i took the milkmans whole 
wagon horse too and my brother butch stole a cement mixer once 
somebody watched him and got him pinched him and the junkyard guy 
he sold it to 
panczko said he once paid a policeman a 1000 bribe to overlook 
the heist of a load of socks from the trunk of a salesmans car 
and then got only 20 for the socks 
damn cops thats where all my money went he complained 
gangster member lindberg the official historian of the chicago 
white sox smiled 
dicks writing a true history of the chicago police said 
reilly hell probably be arrested 
gangster member harold rubin of cicero does some filching too 
but he does his legally moving in on former mobowned buildings 
one step ahead of the wreckers 
a dealer in al capone memorabilia rubin isnt content with the 
small trophies like guns autographs and capones barbers straight 
razor he wants the impressive stuff too 
i just went into the old 4811 club in cicero the old 
gambling dive and i got some great items he said i got the 
26 table thats the dice game you played against the young ladies 
with the big busts you wouldnt know if you won or lost i also 
got the cell door 
cell door 
yeah they had this jail cell in the basement for guys who 
couldnt pay their tabs he said i pulled the door out of a 
couple of feet of water 
rubin said one of his coups was removing the interior marble 
from the lexington hotel a onetime capone headquarters 
kenan heise a chicago tribune obituary editor and historian 
spoke of another caponeowned hotel the metropole 
it was a beautiful place in its day and when my first book 
came out in 1971 i gave the publication party there he 
remembered it was a whorehouse by then though and i had a 
little trouble explaining what kind of party i wanted 
