<TEXT>
citizens of tver and dozens of other 
soviet cities are casting off the names and symbols of a painful 
past 
the people of this ancient city 100 miles northwest of moscow 
started by taking back the name it bore for centuries before stalin 
called it kalinin for a henchman born near tver 
to catherine the great the city was the most beautiful in the 
empire after st petersburg now leningrad because of its 18th 
century architecture as the namesake of mikhail kalinin it became 
a reminder of repression and death 
gorky street in moscow the capitals main thoroughfare has 
been changed back to tverskaya street fashionable shops and stores 
lined the street before the bolshevik revolution and outside the 
city it became the main road to tver 
on july 19 the front page of kalininskaya pravda the local 
newspaper carried a decree signed by boris n yeltsin president 
of the russian republic it said the republics presidium 
decrees rename the city kalinin to the city tver 
yeltsin had reversed half a century and fulfilled a dream of 
many residents 
a poem published with the decree said well goodbye kalinin 
you were just a pseudonym of our returning tver 
now even the newspaper will have to call itself something else 
the name game is sweeping this vast country for decades 
cities streets ships farms and factories were renamed for 
bolshevik heroes and officials 
then as political times changed under mikhail s gorbachev and 
history was rewritten some of the officials were disgraced and the 
circle was completed 
naberezhni chelny renamed brezhnev was returned to its 
original name tsaritsyn renamed stalingrad became volgograd 
other name changes actual or likely include the emergence of old 
samara from kuibyshev nizhny novgorod from gorky transformation 
of kirov to vzyatka sverdlovsk to old ekaterinburg andropov to 
rybinsk the rescue of marnupol from zhdanov lugansk from 
voroshilovgrad and vladikavkaz from ordzhonikidze 
some people who are fed up with the old order even want to 
change leningrad back to st petersburg 
the name of mikhail kalinin the soviet president in 19381946 
was attached to many places other than tver which became kalinin 
on his birthday in 1931 
koenigsberg a historic german city incorporated into the soviet 
union at the end of world war ii became kaliningrad major streets 
in other soviet cities including moscow honor kalinin 
he was a figurehead president hated by victims of the 
collectivization of agriculture a dark period in the countrys 
history 
millions of people were arrested and executed as enemies of 
the people during the collectivization of the 1930s including 
many from kalinins home region some of the bodies are believed to 
have been dumped into mass unmarked graves near tver 
the campaign to regain kalinins old name began in the 1960s 
but did not get far until gorbachev and glasnost came along eleven 
engineers and intellectuals founded a group called return in march 
1988 with that as its goal 
boris yershov a leader of the group and a local legislator 
said returns members were described at first as extremists 
sometimes as hooligans 
people asked how could you insult the memory of mikhail 
kalinin a leading figure in the party government and society 
yershov said 
when we said he wasnt a leading figure of the party and the 
government people just didnt believe us people were so fooled by 
the propaganda for years for decades about our leaders they 
just didnt accept our words 
support for return gradually increased yershov said and people 
began asking if kalinin is not the person hes made out to be 
why do we bear his name why such a supreme honor to a person who 
promoted stalins crimes 
more than 14000 of the citys 475000 people signed a petition 
last year demanding it be called tver again local party and 
legislative bodies eventually gave their support and the idea was 
ratified by yeltsin a radical reformer elected president of 
russia the countrys largest republic in june 
residents interviewed the day yeltsins decree was published 
said the move was welcome but they also wanted other changes 
im not in a festive mood said natalya drozdenko a woman 
in her mid30s waiting in a long line to buy chickens 
its only right to change the name and we have been struggling 
for it lending our signatures to petitions etcetera but somehow 
i understand its only symbolic and it wont affect our 
wellbeing 
alexander bartyenyev an 84yearold world war ii veteran 
strolling past the shops remembers when the city was still called 
tver and said mikhail kalinin never deserved the honor 
kalinin was treated as one of our own bartyenyev said he 
was born here and worked here but as president of the country he 
could not stop the bloodletting 
yershov said his organization now would turn its attention to 
restoring monuments churches and the old street names 
</TEXT>
