<TEXT>
dutch customs officials have 
enlisted a chemical fingerprinting method to spot any iraqi or 
kuwaiti oil smuggled into rotterdam europes largest oil port in 
violation of sanctions 
the method relies on a process known as gas chromatography and 
is already used by oil companies and by a government agency trying 
to identify sources of north sea oil pollution customs service 
spokesman cornelis verlaan said thursday 
verlaan told the associated press the customs laboratory in 
amsterdam now plans to use the technique to check samples of crude 
oil shipments arriving in rotterdam 
in line with the aug 6 un embargo the netherlands has banned 
all iraqi and kuwaiti oil imports and transshipments through 
rotterdam europes largest refining center and site of a huge oil 
spot market the un action was to punish iraqi for its miitary 
takeover of kuwait on aug 2 
verlaan said it takes five to six weeks for an oil tanker to 
reach rotterdam so no oil loaded after aug 7 has arrived here 
yet 
the identification process is based on differences in texture 
and chemical composition found in every oil fields deposits 
verlaan said samples taken in rotterdam will be compared with a 
file of about 40 crude samples including those from iraq and 
kuwait 
you kind of take a fingerprint said verlaan if were in 
a real hurry we can conduct an analysis in 24 hours 
he said the procedure is now about 80 percent accurate adding 
were refining the technique all the time 
verlaan conceded that crude oil could be tampered with on its 
way to rotterdam but said you would see an entirely different 
picture than with oil that hasnt been doctored 
oil companies are using the process to check on the origin of 
their crude 
the traffic and waterways ministry has been using the gas 
chromatography technique to trace ships suspected of causing north 
sea oil spills verlaan said 
</TEXT>
