editors note the steady stream of us air power to the middle 
east is dependent on midair refueling national writer fred bayles 
was aboard an air force tanker as it rendezvoused with combat 
aircraft on their way to the military buildup 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
there is little time for ceremony 
while traveling 530 mph five miles above the ocean 
pinch 15 are you full asked the airman first class 
operating the refueling boom of the air force kc135 tanker 
pinch 15 is full disconnecting said the pilot of the f4 
phantom fighter flying a scant 20 feet below the pilots face was 
hidden by his helmet visor and oxygen mask as the graceful gray 
aircraft severed its connection to the tanker in a spray of jet 
fuel 
good journey said the boom operator and the phantom was 
gone 
the brief ritual is being repeated often over the atlantic these 
days while the technological miracle of airtoair refueling has 
long been commonplace the difference is these pilots are flying to 
an uncertainty that may include combat 
we train to do this all the time said the tankers boom 
operator a 22yearold massachusetts woman but it makes it a 
little more urgent when its the real thing 
thursdays mission by the plattsburgh ny air force base crew 
was one of untold numbers conducted as the us military buildup 
grows in the iraq crisis 
the refueling of the 24 phantoms involved eight kc135s from 
plattsburgh along with eight from griffiss afb in new york and 
pease afb in new hampshire 
details about the total number of missions is classified lt 
col rick oborn an air force spokesman at the pentagon would only 
say the number of refueling sorties is well above normal military 
activity 
secrecy was a passenger on thursdays flight journalists aboard 
the tanker were asked not to use the names of the crew or identify 
the squadron squadron emblems and identification patches were 
removed from the flight crews uniforms 
potential terrorist reprisals explained base spokesman lt 
casey mahon 
