thursdays receivers were phantoms known as wild weasels based 
at george afb outside los angeles the fighters are loaded with 
electronic gear and arms for the highrisk job of disrupting and 
destroying enemy radar and antiaircraft installations 
that deadly business was made apparent as the thirsty fighters 
swung into formation with the tankers 190 miles east of cape cod 
each of the sharpnosed aircraft carried gleaming white missiles 
under its wings 
inside the cavernous tanker the 22yearold boom operator took 
her position in the tail of the plane lying on a platform to 
maneuver the 20foot refueling boom into a port just behind a 
fighters canopy 
the nimble jet eased into position by listening to quick curt 
instructions from the operator and watching red green and white 
directional signals flashing from the tankers belly 
with three fighters flying in formation with the tanker she ran 
through the routine for more than an hour loading each plane with 
900 gallons of jp4 fuel then adding 400 gallons to top off the 
fighters already emptying fuel tanks 
when the process was finished the jets had been dragged 560 
more miles across the ocean it was time to turn for home other 
tankers were waiting along the flight path to escort the fighters 
farther along their journey 
and despite the protestations that this was just another 
mission the thoughts of the tankers crew turned to where the 
fighters were heading 
i know what theyre going over there for and i think about 
them said the planes captain were over here in our safe 
united states and theyre asked to do a lot more than we are right 
now 
