<TEXT>
the agriculture department has used socalled 
federal marketing orders to give generations of fruit and vegetable 
farmers a way to boost prices but officials say that application 
is less prevalent than before 
through federal marketing orders the department can affect the 
volume quality appearance packaging or public perception of 
about 45 fruit and vegetable crops worth about 45 billion a year 
its a touchy subject defenders of marketing orders insist the 
programs assure consumers of consistent supplies and high quality 
but others claim the system promotes greed and waste by 
providing indirect subsidies to favored industries 
federal marketing orders for horticultural crops as fruits and 
vegetables are collectively called are controls authorized by law 
to let producers in a geographic area decide as a group how and 
sometimes when their crops are sold on the market 
the system is subject to regulations and supervision by the 
agriculture department although local boards carry out the 
daytoday functions 
nicholas j powers of the departments economic research service 
says the controls were sanctioned by congress in the early 1930s 
following earlier attempts by western cooperatives to withhold 
produce and limit market sales when supplies were abundant 
but those attempts failed because not everyone went along with 
the coop efforts and the us supreme court threw out early laws 
on controls and taxes for processing 
congress finally devised the agricultural marketing agreement 
act of 1937 the underlying basis for todays marketing orders and 
agreements 
in a report published this month in farmline magazine powers 
outlined the different kinds of marketing orders virtually all the 
orders allow growers to set minimum grade and size requirements in 
many handlers pay for advertising and promotion programs and for 
research on production and marketing 
twentyone marketing orders allow growers to apply some kind of 
volume control to limit the amount sent to market during certain 
times of the year 
consumers who buy produce in markets with limited quantities 
pay a higher price than otherwise powers said 
a few years ago federal marketing orders generated court 
challenges and other snarls in one case surplus navel oranges 
were used as livestock feed after being barred from the market 
the conservative heritage foundation in 1985 called federal 
marketing orders governmentbacked cartels that forced 
consumers to pay millions of dollars more for food than they would 
otherwise 
but there has been less flak about marketing orders lately and 
powers in a telephone interview thursday suggested some reasons 
why 
over the last decade theres been less emphasis on what are 
called the volumecontrol regulations he said those are the 
regulations which can be used to restrict supply to certain markets 
and thereby elevate prices in those markets 
marketing orders now tend to emphasize more of the 
advertising promotional activities along with the grading of 
produce to make sure crops are mature enough for sale to users 
powers said also more orders emphasize research and packaging of 
the produce 
but volume controls are still used last winter he said news 
reports described how california was controlling the amount of 
citrus going to market even after freezing weather had devastated 
so much of the florida citrus crop 
volume controls are still used in some of the orders but much 
less vigorously now than just a few years ago powers said 
powers says the decline in the use of marketing orders also is 
due in part to usda policy which does not encourage the industry 
to use volume controls as vigorously as they had in the past 
one alternative generally favored by usda is the use of 
marketing orders to formulate promotion and research programs 
which are paid for by the industry itself 
the 1985 farm law for example authorized such a national 
program for watermelons administered by the departments 
agricultural marketing service 
a few of the crops covered by federal marketing orders include 
florida citrus and tomatoes california peaches pears and plums 
california and arizona navel oranges idaho and east oregon 
potatoes georgia peaches virginia and north carolina potatoes 
maine potatoes peanuts grown in 16 states and hawaiian papayas 
</TEXT>
