<TEXT>
salvadoran rebel leaders say they 
will ask president alfredo cristiani to accept un human rights 
observers as a condition for an immediate ceasefire in el 
salvadors decadeold civil war 
the proposal will be presented later today when the latest round 
of peace talks begins in san jose according to miguel saenz a 
spokesman for the leftist farabundo marti national liberation front 
if the salvadoran government accepts that such a commission 
oversee observance of human rights in the country then agreement 
could be reached for a ceasefire at this meeting saenz said 
thursday 
the fiveday meeting under un mediation is the fourth round 
of talks between the rebels and the government since cristiani took 
office last year 
the previous rounds ended in deadlock with the government 
insisting the rebels enter into a ceasefire agreement before any 
other issues were discussed 
rebel leaders have demanded political reform principally that 
the government purge the armed forces of rightist elements and 
bring human rights violators to justice 
saenz said that establishing a un human rights commission in 
el salvador would be an effective way of getting around the 
deadlock 
human rights groups say 73000 people have died since el 
salvadors civil war began in 1979 and nearly half were civilians 
slain by the military or rightist death squads for suspected 
leftist sympathies 
last november six jesuit priests were roused from their beds at 
night in their university campus home in san salvador and shot dead 
by uniformed soldiers along with their housekeeper and her daughter 
the assassinations took place at the height of a guerrilla 
assault on the salvadoran capital and while that section of the 
city was under military control and a dusktodawn curfew 
meanwhile in el salvador repair crews today were restoring 
power to large sections of the country blacked out by guerrilla 
sabotage earlier this week 
officials of the stateowned lempa executive commission said the 
rebels attacked 17 main transmission lines knocking out power to 
nearly half of the small central american nation of 5 million 
people 
