four sheriffs a deputy sheriff and a 
police chief caught up in an fbi sting codenamed walking short 
have been charged with setting up a protection racket for drug 
traffickers 
two fbi agents acting as chicago businessmen interested in 
shipping cocaine led the yearlong sting whose name was inspired by 
the 1973 movie walking tall about a tennessee sheriff who did 
not cave in to corruption around him 
forty fbi agents fanned out through four contiguous eastern 
kentucky counties to make the arrests thursday the six were 
indicted on charges of conspiracy drug distribution and taking 
money to protect drug traffickers 
us attorney louie defalaise said the arrests demonstrated 
the absolute corrupting influence of drugs 
arrested were lee county sheriff johnny mann 39 breathitt 
county sheriff dean spencer 46 wolfe county sheriff lester drake 
51 owsley county sheriff billy mcintosh 57 beattyville police 
chief omer noe and wolfe county deputy sheriff wilson stone 
at a hearing thursday five of the men were released on bail 
ranging from 5000 to 20000 mann the alleged ringleader was 
denied bail after an undercover agent testified he had threatened 
to kill anyone who set him up 
according to the indictment agents paid the law officers more 
than 85000 to protect a phony cocaine and marijuana smuggling 
operation from police interference 
at one point cocaine packages were dropped by air onto a farm 
owned by one of the officers authorities said 
defalaise said the cocaine which totaled nearly 250 pounds was 
never distributed for sale to the public 
most of the drug counts carry up to life in prison the major 
conspiracy and extortion charges carry up to 20 years 
