<TEXT>
following is a look at 10 of 23 soviets whose 
citizenship has been restored by soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev the names of the 13 others affected by the decree were 
not announced 
alexander solzhenitsyn 71 author of the gulag 
archipelago a searing expose of the horrors of dictator josef 
stalins prison camps the winner of the nobel prize for literature 
in 1970 he was charged with treason in 1974 stripped of his 
citizenship and expelled he was constantly harassed by the kgb 
secret police and finally was forced onto a plane to germany and 
stripped of his citizenship the next day the gulag archipelago 
was published in the soviet union last year other works include 
one day in the life of ivan denisovich cancer ward the 
first circle and august 1914 a narrative of russian life and 
the nations stark unpreparedness for the military offensive 
launched against germany in that year 
valeri chalidze 51 a founding member of the human rights 
committee whose citizenship was revoked while he was on a tour of 
the united states in 1972 he wrote to defend these rights 
about human rights and now runs an emigre publishing house in 
vermont 
lev kopelev solzhenitsyns prison friend and a scholar of 
german literature who left the soviet union in november 1980 with 
his wife raisa orlova both lost their citizenship in 1981 and 
moved to west germany where kopelev lives his wife died last 
year kopelevs writings include to be preserved forever a 
restrospective about the soviet union and we lived in moscow 
vladimir voinovich a satirist who emigrated to west germany in 
1980 after being expelled from the soviet writers union in 1974 
he was expelled after the publication abroad of his world war ii 
novel the adventures of private ivan chonkin other works 
include the ivankiad about an attempt to get an extra room in 
a moscow apartment moscow 2042 a projection of the future 
and the fur hat a satire on privilege in soviet society he 
was invited back to the soviet union last year for a visit 
victor korchnoi 54 one of the soviet unions leading chess 
players who defected in 1976 in the netherlands his matches 
against the official soviet champion anatoly karpov became famous 
as duels on political psychological and physical levels he was 
twice an unsuccessful challenger of karpov as titleholder in the 
world championship finals and now ranks 12th worldwide 
georgi vladimov 59 one of the leading writers of the magazine 
yunost during the 1960s he came into conflict with soviet 
authorities over foreign publication of his works one work is 
faithful ruslan a short novel told through the eyes of a guard 
dog in a prison camp 
yuri orlov a prominent member of the dissident movement he 
was one of the founders of the helsinki monitoring group in moscow 
arrested and exiled for his human rights work he was allowed to 
leave for the united states after the soviets released american 
journalist nick daniloff 
oskar rabin was one of the organizers of a nonconformist art 
exhibit in moscow that was bulldozed in 1974 he was later forced 
to emigrate 
vasily aksyonov author of the 1960 bestseller kollegi was 
criticized by soviet authorities for his bad language which 
actually was the slang of soviet youth he emigrated after a brush 
with the authorities in 1980 other works include the burn 
about a young boy who grew up in moscow and in stalins labor 
camps the satirical novel the island of crimea and in 
search of melancholy baby about his emigre life he made his 
first trip back to the soviet union last year and plans another 
when his play heron is produced in moscow next year 
valeri tarsis who was awarded citizenship posthumously was a 
correspondent during world war ii and a shortstory writer he 
demanded permission to emigrate in 1961 was detained in a 
psychiatric hospital under nikita s khrushchev and expelled from 
the soviet union in the late 1960s he died in switzerland in 1983 
</TEXT>
