<TEXT>
the federal communications commission is 
investigating complaints against a public tv station for showing 
some of robert mapplethorpes most sexually explicit photos 
wgbh showed the pictures in a 10 pm news broadcast july 31 
the day before the opening here of an exhibit of the late artists 
work which includes homosexual and sadomasochistic images and 
child nudes 
the fcc has not decided whether to take any action against the 
station said roger holberg an fcc attorney 
the traveling exhibit now on display at the institute of 
contemporary art has generated a storm of protests since it became 
a focus of sen jesse helms crusade against federal funding of art 
deemed indecent 
later the director of a cincinnati gallery that exhibited the 
photographs was arrested on obscenity charges he is awaiting trial 
leading the list of three complaints to the fcc was one by the 
rev donald wildmon head of the american family association in 
tupelo miss 
a letter from wildmon a longtime critic of alleged indeceny in 
media described the broadcast as nothing more than the 
sensational presentation of potentially obscene material 
eric brass attorney for wgbh defended the broadcast 
it just is not obscene brass said thursday i believe we 
have the right to do what we did in the context of a serious news 
program we cannot be in the position of censoring debate about 
censorship 
if material is judged to be obscene it can be banned from being 
broadcast holberg said but material deemed to be indecent is 
given more leeway as long as it is not shown before 8 pm when 
children are more likely to be watching 
congress told the agency last year to restrict broadcasting of 
indecent material 24 hours a day the new rule was challenged by 
broadcasters and other groups and a federal appeals court in 
washington is studying whether it can be enforced 
mapplethorpe put together the exhibit shortly before he died of 
aids last year at age 42 the 124 photographs are mainly portraits 
and pictures of flowers but about a quarter of them are sexually 
graphic 
we wanted to let the public know what the controversy was 
about and let them decide for themselves said julie eggleston a 
spokeswoman for the tv station wgbh as a part of the public 
broadcasting service receives federal funds 
