<TEXT>
japan is considering breaking with its longheld 
policy against deployment of military equipment overseas as it 
considers responses to the persian gulf crisis a foreign ministry 
official said friday 
ministry spokesman taizo watanabe told reporters he did not 
preclude the possibility the government was considering sending 
minesweepers to the middle east 
asked about the constitutionality of this he said to make it 
a reality we have to go through various heated discussions among 
various agencies in the government as well as take into 
consideration the public opinion of japan if there is any 
difference of opinion on constitutionality we go down to the roots 
of the discussion and find out whether it is constitutional or not 
that is what we are doing right now 
japans postwar constitution bars the use of force as a means of 
settling international disputes and forbids the maintenance of 
land air and sea forces since the early 1950s that has been 
interpreted as allowing a purely defensive military 
current law also restricts the selfdefense forces japans 
military to japanese territory except for participation in 
ceremonial occasions overseas 
changes in the law would likely bring a strong reaction from 
japanese opposition parties and neighboring countries opposed to a 
greater role for japans military 
foreign minister taro nakayama began a nineday trip to the 
middle east on friday to visit countries affected by the 
iraqkuwait crisis his mission is to determine what actions japan 
can take to help the international effort to punish iraq for 
invading kuwait watanabe said 
japanese news reports said the sending of minesweepers could be 
seen as a defensive act needed to protect japans oil supply japan 
imports 99 percent of the oil it uses and is more dependent on 
middle east oil than any industrialized nation 
japans military remains controversial here and increases in 
defense spending are hotly debated asian nations invaded by japan 
during world war ii also have opposed increases in japans military 
strength 
japan previously has sent nonmilitary personnel to join 
peacekeeping or monitoring forces in nambia nicaragua and along 
the afghan border 
watanabe said japanese public opinion once sharply opposed to 
any kind of military involvement overseas has changed that kind 
of opposition which i have seen before is much much less these 
days he said 
