<TEXT>
roving bands with makeshift 
shields guns and spears rampaged through soweto and other black 
townships friday clashing in sporadic battles that have killed 183 
people in six days 
police in armored vehicles rolled over streets barricaded with 
boulders and burning cars they used tear gas to disperse shouting 
mobs and fired shotguns at combatants fleeing through narrow 
shantytown streets 
police said at least 31 people had been killed and 217 injured 
in two days of savage handtohand fighting in soweto south 
africas largest black township 
the fighting pits zulu supporters of the conservative inkatha 
movement against mostly xhosa members of the african national 
congress led by nelson mandela 
the anc accused the governments security forces of plotting to 
use the zulubased inkatha party to stir up tribal rivalry in the 
townships 
more than 5000 people have died in fighting between inkatha and 
anc supporters in the eastern natal province in the past five years 
their bloody conflict spread to the township of thokoza east of 
johannesburg on sunday and later to four more areas including 
soweto southwest of johannesburg 
groups of up to 100 armed men waved sticks knives bayonets and 
shields fashioned of trashcan lids as they marched most of the 
combatants were zulu migrant workers from the inkatha stronghold of 
natal or xhosa residents of soweto 
on friday afternoon hundreds of inkatha supporters moved out of 
their compounds and stood on the railway track with guns and 
sticks waiting for the trains to bring black commuters home from 
johannesburg the south african press association reported 
police and residents also reported looting random 
gasolinebombing of homes and indiscriminate gang attacks on 
individuals a family of six including a 5monthold baby and 
three other children were badly burned when someone threw a 
firebomb into their shack in kagiso township north of soweto 
the anc said state security forces in collusion with inkatha 
were trying to spread a climate of fear and terror in towns 
that are anc strongholds 
they want to provoke a mass backlash among blacks and whites 
in support of tough repressive measures by the government in order 
to undermine the process towards peace the anc statement said 
the spreading unrest led to an unscheduled meeting thursday 
between president fw de klerk and mandela who have been holding 
discussions to clear the way for formal negotiations on ending 
white minority rule 
inkatha president mangosuthu buthelezi said anc supporters 
frequently insult denigrate and attack inkatha members on the 
trains in the buses and other places he said that had sparked 
the conflict 
buthelezi making his statement in ulundi in natal province 
said inkatha was committed to democracy and opposed to violence 
but he said until respect for one another is observed it will be 
difficult to obtain peace 
