<TEXT>
editors note us air power heading to the middle east is 
turning sections of the atlantic sky into crowded midair service 
stations national writer fred bayles was aboard an air force 
tanker to view the busy refueling operations off the east coast 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
this usually lonely patch of air is 
suddenly buzzing with the hum of faraway crisis 
the ocean below is empty except for the shadows of clouds five 
miles above the sky is filled with planes echelons of thirsty 
dartshaped fighters chase matronly tanker planes loaded with fuel 
radio channels crackle with curt instructions 
the deployment of us military air power to the middle east has 
turned the skies off the east coast into busy service station 
stops where fighters hook up to transport planes for a fillup at 
530 mph 
theres considerably increased activity in tanking 
operations said lt col george peck a spokesman for the 
strategic air command which operates the air force tankers it 
is an integral part of this operation 
the increased activity was obvious from aboard a kc135 tanker 
based at the plattsburgh ny air force base which took part in a 
refueling operation thursday 
the tanker was one of 16 from plattsburgh griffiss air force 
base in new york and pease air force base in new hampshire that 
formed an air bridge across the empty ocean for a flight of 24 f4 
phantom fighters 
pairs of tankers called cells could be seen spread across the 
horizon each plane was followed by three fighters 
it was a big operation said the captain who piloted the 
tanker a military cousin of the old 707 airliner three cells 
were operating pretty close in the same area and we were hearing on 
the radio of other cells coming up it was a continuous operation 
the captain whose name was not disclosed for security reasons 
said it was an example of what the tankers can do 
thats what our job is we can get where we need to be unload 
the gas and let the bombers fighters and cargo airplanes go off 
and do their mission she said 
the increase in military air activity has had only slight impact 
on commercial air travel 
there have been minor delays in some traffic but not any big 
disruptions said jo ann sloane a spokeswoman for the federal 
aviation administration 
the tankers in thursdays mission traveled across new england to 
a point 190 miles east of cape cod where they rendezvoused with the 
days receivers a squadron of fighters taking off from seymour 
johnson air force base in north carolina 
the f4g phantoms based at george air force base outside los 
angeles were wild weasels specially equipped with electronics 
and armaments for the dangerous task of disrupting and destroying 
enemy radar and antiaircraft installations 
the gleaming white missiles under their wings highlighted the 
fact this was no practice mission 
inside the hot noisy tanker which flew its first mission 
before any of its crew was born an airman first class took her 
position in the tail of the plane lying on a platform to maneuver 
the 20foot refueling boom into a port just behind the fighters 
canopy 
she nursed the jet into place with brief directions over the 
radio and a series of red green and white directional signals 
flashing from the tankers belly 
with this many planes operating in the area you dont want to 
have a lot of chatter she explained 
she repeated the delicate maneuvers for more than an hour 
loading three fighters with 900 gallons of jp4 fuel then adding 
another 400 gallons to top off the fighters already emptying fuel 
tanks 
the process which covered another 560 miles to the east is 
known in air force slang as dragging them across the pond 
when the job was done the kc135 turned for home other 
tankers were waiting to escort the fighters the rest of the way 
across the ocean 
good journey said the boom operator as the fighters veered 
away their mission done there was little emotion over the 
prospect of where the fighters were headed 
we train to do this all the time said the boom operator 
but it makes it a little more urgent when its the real thing 
</TEXT>
