<TEXT>
up to 38 commercial airliners are being turned 
over to the military to haul troops and cargo the first time in 
history part of the us civil air fleet has been diverted for this 
purpose the pentagon announced friday night 
the decision was made by the commanderinchief of the us 
transportation command and military airlift command gen ht 
johnson to meet the growing airlift requirements for us 
forces deployed in the middle east a defense department statement 
said 
the move means that as many as 38 civilian airplanes may be 
turned over to the pentagon to use as cargo and troop transports 
those planes are owned by 16 airlines which also will be providing 
the crews to operate them 
the airlift support is expected to be needed for several weeks 
the pentagon said 
this is the first use of the civil reserve air fleet since the 
program was conceived in the 1950s under the program airlines 
prepare and commit specific aircraft that can be used to carry 
troops and military cargo in times of crisis the airlines are 
reimbursed 
the program includes 29 airlines but in this first initial stage 
of the program only 16 carriers are involved the statement said 
it did not identify the airlines involved 
johnsons action activates the lowest stage of the program 
the program is designed with three stages so the airlift command 
can tailor the airlift force needed for any contingency the 
pentagon statement said 
the initial stage calls for the civilian airlines that are part 
of the program to provide planes within 24 hours of the request 
the planes will be used to augment the military airlift 
commands routine overseas missions as well as for operations in 
the middle east the statement said 
pentagon spokesman pete williams asked why the pentagon was 
forced to make the move said gen johnson needs more planes 
military commanders at the pentagon had begun to complain that 
they werent capable of moving enough of their troops quickly 
because of transportation shortages even though the troops were 
fully ready to go to saudi arabia 
