<TEXT>
its no accident when a drunken driver 
gets into a car wreck florida officials have conceded in a 
warofwords victory for mothers against drunk driving its a 
crash 
florida state troopers and the department of highway safety and 
motor vehicles will no longer refer to collisions between vehicles 
as accidents partly because of pressure from madd theyre now 
known as crashes 
accidents implies that the vehicles are out there acting 
independently through some unseen forces said department 
spokesman ed birk theres almost always a human factor and a 
human reason behind the crash 
the department has begun referring to all collisions as 
crashes not just those involving drunks birk said but he 
conceded that years of coaxing from madd played a big part in the 
decision 
the antidrunken driving organization has long sought to 
convince governments and news reporters that wrecks involving 
alcohol arent accidents 
it is important that people not think of it as something that 
couldnt be helped said betty jane spencer of florida madd 
some of them are accidents but not drunk driving 
florida state troopers were told in a july 18 memo from director 
bobby burkett to begin using the word crash in all 
correspondence and when they speak about a collision publicly 
the justpublished book of statewide statistics on wrecks has 
been retitled florida traffic crash facts and the former 
traffic accident report forms used by police agencies across the 
state will soon be known as traffic crash report forms 
a vast majority of crashes are not accidents birk said 
theres a human being behind the wheel thats got to be 
responsible 
the only other state to adopt crash as the official word for 
a car wreck is missouri said madd national president mickey sadoff 
for 10 years weve fought for this word change because to 
call it an accident seems to absolve people of responsibility 
she said by calling it a crash you are elevating it to show 
its a preventable violent crime 
mrs spencer who lost four children in a drunkendriving wreck 
said madd members often write letters to newspapers and tv stations 
when reporters refer to such collisions as accidents 
its very offensive to people who have lost loved ones to call 
it an accident she said i think now that the state is 
starting to use crash the news people will start feeling more 
comfortable with it 
there were 36312 alcoholrelated collisions in florida in 1989 
down from 37800 the year before according to the new crash 
facts book almost 1500 people died in those collisions which 
represented 144 percent of total wrecks 
