<TEXT>
injecting insulin glands into a transplanted 
liver prevents diabetes in some patients a procedure that could 
help diabetics who have kidney damage researchers said thursday 
the islets of langerhans the tiny insulin factories found in 
the pancreas were injected into the livers of nine patients whose 
pancreases were removed at two pittsburgh hospitals 
all nine patients produced insulin at first and for five of 
them bloodsugar levels remained normal and insulin shots were 
unnecessary according to a study published this week in the 
lancet a british medical journal 
doctors from the universities of pittsburgh miami and milan 
italy said fk506 a drug that prevents rejection of transplanted 
organs and glands contributed to the operations success 
gerold grodsky a researcher of islet gland function at the 
university of california at san francisco called the study a 
major step 
however he cautioned that the procedure will be useful only for 
people who are taking antirejection drugs such as kidney 
transplant recipients a third of whom have diabetes 
the patients in the study had lost their pancreases spleens 
stomachs and parts of their small and large intestines to abdominal 
cancer and had received liver transplants 
the surgery next will be tried on patients with kidney damage 
due to diabetes that appears early in life an associate professor 
of surgery at the university of pittsburgh said 
the real target of the research eventually is juvenile 
diabetes the most troublesome kind said dr andreas tzakis 
one percent of the us population suffers from juvenile 
diabetes which can cause blindness heart problems and kidney 
failure the procedures success is less promising for them because 
their bodies would reject donor glands grodsky said 
more research on the bodys immune system is needed before 
people with juvenile diabetes but no transplants can be helped 
said dr daniel mintz of the university of miamis diabetes center 
another of the studys authors 
in the lancet study two patients died of infections and 
multiple organ failure and a third died after six months when his 
cancer reappeared another patient became diabetic later 
the researchers said the best example of how the gland 
transplant works is seen in mary arthur 16 of louisville ky 
who underwent a transplant in january to replace a liver diseased 
with cancer 
the transplant of the islets of langerhans takes only 30 
minutes the cells either are injected into a small blood vessel 
near the liver during surgery or delivered intravenously the study 
said 
the islets seem to be making a new home in the liver although 
its not their normal home tzakis said they go there to live 
and they get a blood supply in there 
preparing the islets takes four hours the cells comprising 
only 1 percent of the pancreas and visible only with a microscope 
are removed from a dead donors pancreas 
dr paul lacey a pathologist at washington university in st 
louis said the study confirms results a washington university team 
published in the april issue of the journal diabetes 
the washington researchers transplanted the islets of langerhans 
into a diabetic patient with kidney damage then recorded a 
reduction in blood sugar when insulin production resumed lacey 
said 
</TEXT>
