<TEXT>
life in the business marsh which ordinarily 
hums with innovative little outfits that eventually grow and nip at 
the heels of giant companies is quiet these days 
business isnt good for beginners many dont even get a hearing 
from the loan officer at the bank venture capitalists those folks 
who used to take big risks for big rewards havent been very 
venturesome either 
the federal reserve following a tight money policy has made 
life miserable for them and banks fearful of regulators and often 
reacting to their own earlier excesses have all but welded the 
hinges on their vaults 
congress has hindered rather than helped not only has it failed 
to solve the deficit problem it is poised now to pile on a whole 
new set of regulations that can only raise costs and drive 
smallbusiness people mad 
the regulations all accompanied by energydraining paperwork 
concern minimum wages mandated health costs mandated leaves 
mandated access for handicapped mandated pollution controls the 
paperwork alone is full time 
an american express co survey of newbusiness formation showed 
a 42 percent decline in the second half of 1989 dun amp bradstreet 
corp says new incorporations are stagnant in the first four 
months of 1990 they totaled 236102 down 09 percent from 238306 
in the yearearlier period 
business failures meanwhile are higher for the first time 
since 1986 dampb puts the percentage at 95 percent over last year 
and as usual many of these are upstart companies in april the 
new england failure rate was nearly triple that of a year earlier 
and the middle atlantic rate was more than double 
small and beginning business is the breeding ground of 
creativity the source of new jobs the inventor of new products 
and services and the future competition for big companies that 
otherwise might develop clogged arteries 
from emerging businesses will come new ways to contain 
healthcare costs new hightech companies to solve what has 
stymied the bigger guys new products to help the balance of 
payments new marketing strategies 
economists accustomed to the big scene to viewing abstract 
statistics to dealing with macro rather than microeconomics 
often make little of the emergingbusiness problem everyone 
suffers in a downturn they say 
others contend correctly that much of the credit crunch 
involves real estate and building and that many forestalled 
ventures are speculative whatever they involve the future of jobs 
and companies 
no area of the economy exists in isolation 
the construction of one house for example involves a thousand 
economic transactions including the purchase of raw land payment 
of fees to towns soil testing sewers water mains curbs 
gutters streets landscaping 
it involves according to the national association of home 
builders 18 manyears of employment including the direct 
services of carpenters plumbers electricians insulators 
painters roofers cement workers tilers and others 
the jobs and the businesses involved are by no means local 
steelmakers carpetmakers furnace makers and makers of air 
conditioners must ship their products from many miles away by air 
by rail by road 
but it isnt just real estate and building that are being 
deprived of water in the smallbusiness marsh it isnt only 
hightech companies either 
when business withers at the grass roots the damage sometimes 
isnt seen for a while big business can shout threaten and stamp 
its feet thus getting the the attention of elected officials the 
smallest businesses might not 
when ideas and innovations die when inventions arent financed 
when startup companies arent nourished the signs might be barely 
detectible in the national statistics 
the economic measuring devices arent always so perceptive that 
they can detect the pulse of small business the faint murmurs in 
the business marsh 
</TEXT>
