<TEXT>
with the price of petroleum rising and crude 
supplies falling are oil company stocks a good bet during the 
mideast crisis 
that depends 
most experts say shares of the major integrated oil 
companies such as exxon mobil and chevron should be a safe 
investment for the near term in fact many of these stocks are 
considered undervalued 
but some suggest it may be wise to avoid companies that are 
primarily involved in refining crude such as diamond shamrock rampm 
these companies it is argued may be caught in the squeeze between 
the steeper prices they must pay for crude and pressure they face 
to hold down prices at the pump 
while major oil companies may be in a good position investing 
in these stocks is not riskfree analysts say 
its absolutely not the place to make a quick buck said 
frank knuettel who follows oil companies at prudentialbache 
securities inc 
for one thing oil companies face profit pressures as they 
replace supplies gathered before iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
with higherprice oil 
in addition the oil giants are under increasing pressure by 
both the government and consumer groups to hold down gasoline 
prices amid charges of price gouging 
finally nobody knows whether the higher prices will cause a 
steep dropoff in demand for gasoline and other refined products 
that could crimp the bottom line 
higher prices and the potential for higher taxes will all work 
on demand said bear stearns amp co analyst stephen smith 
but the oil giants should be able to navigate around most of 
these pitfalls analysts say 
replacing crude supplies lost from iraq and kuwait should not be 
a problem said barry sahgal an analyst at the new york brokerage 
ladenburg thalmann amp co inc 
they are so flexible that they can move from one crude source 
to another he said 
in addition analysts say the major oil companies will benefit 
from the rise in crude prices even if they cant pass along all of 
the costs to customers accounting practices allow them to book a 
profit when their production subsidiaries sell the crude at the 
newly higher prices to their refining units 
companies selfsufficient in crude production such as arco 
should particularly benefit smith said while those that have to 
purchase supplies on the world market will benefit less 
knuettel said he believes oil company profits will grow this 
year even if rising prices crimp demand for gasoline and other 
refined products but he is less bullish about buying oil stocks 
than some analysts 
knuettel advises investors holding stock in major integrated oil 
companies to stand pat if the shares are considered a longterm 
investment but if the shares are held in a trading account 
investors should consider selling them to take a profit on days 
when the stock prices are up he said 
the excitement of the moment has caused oil shares to reach 
excessive prices near term he wrote in a recent analysis 
in fact prices of many of the major oil company stocks hit 
52week highs in the days after iraqs invasion of kuwait since 
then they have moderated somewhat 
there was panic buying in the issues said sahgal on the 
belief that the stocks would benefit from the rise in oil prices 
and offer an inflation hedge 
bear stearns said in a report last week that even if oil prices 
average in the low 20 range for the rest of the year energy 
company stocks including gas and coal concerns are not trading at 
prices that reflect their true value the brokerage recommended 
these stocks be purchased aggressively 
</TEXT>
