<TEXT>
the gold cordoba nicaraguas new 
money has stumbled out of the starting gate despite an aggressive 
campaign by the government to bolster confidence in the currency 
nicaraguans seem wary of the gold cordoba which went into 
circulation on monday and with the old cordobas still circulating 
confusion mingles with the uncertainty 
the old cordoba was devalued thursday the 31st time since 
president violeta barrios de chamorro took office april 25 trading 
at 750000 to the dollar from the previous rate of 690000 it was 
bringing up to 800000 to the dollar on managuas flourishing and 
illegal black market 
francisco mayorga the head of nicaraguas central bank said 
the gold cordobas will be backed by dollars and will be exchanged 
on par with the dollar 
mayorga said tying the new currency to the dollar is intended to 
end the string of devaluations and bring some stability to the 
economy 
the government said the devaluations of the old cordoba will 
continue until it is entirely replaced by the new money possibly 
by the end of the year 
on monday 45 million of the new cordobas went into 
circulation representing about 10 percent of the value of the 
money in the country 
state workers received up to 50 gold cordobas as a part of their 
salaries and got the rest in old cordobas 
but the lowest gold cordoba denomination is 5 cordobas equal to 
five dollars a large sum in one of the hemispheres poorest 
countries 
bills of one gold cordoba and less are to begin circulating in 
october but for now nicaraguans spending gold cordobas have to 
take change in the old money at the official rate 
thousands of government employees meanwhile headed to black 
market moneychangers to try to swap the new money for dollars in 
case the new money became devalued but the black marketeers known 
locally as coyotes werent interested 
the gold cordoba cannot be on par with the dollar said one 
the dollar is the world currency and even in underdeveloped 
countries with stable economies the money is not on par with the 
dollar 
the central bank also refused to change the new cordobas for 
dollars saying such a run would deplete its supply 
nicaragua is swimming in virtually worthless cordobas in their 
last year in office the leftist sandinista government stopped 
devaluing them leaving the currency extremely overvalued 
mrs chamorros government began a series of devaluations that 
sent prices for basics soaring leading to two damaging general 
strikes mostly by sandinistaled unions 
</TEXT>
