<TEXT>
an increase in the world supply of crude oil 
will not necessarily translate into plenty of gasoline for the 
united states according to oil industry sources who warned that 
higher prices might persist 
even though oilproducing nations could probably boost their 
output by up to 35 million barrels per day making up for most of 
the 4 million barrels kept off the market by the boycott of iraq 
and kuwait there could be problems in getting the crude refined to 
meet us standards the sources said 
additional production might be the wrong kind of crude or it 
could come from libya and iran which the united states will not do 
business with several executives of a major oil company told 
reporters in a meeting thursday 
the executives who spoke on condition that neither they nor 
their company be identified said refineries that could increase 
output in several foreign countries are also unable to make oil 
products that meet stringent us environmental standards such as 
unleaded gasoline 
there are certain crudes and certain products and certain 
suppliers you cant turn to one of the executives said 
the stuff thats idle today does not serve the purposes of the 
us said another executive 
a spokesman for the american petroleum institute the industrys 
main trade group said refineries generally are geared to take a 
certain type of oil and they try to get that oil theres great 
variation among crudes and refineries he said 
world oil markets have been in a state of chaos with prices 
steadily on the rise after iraq invaded neighboring kuwait on aug 
2 and an international boycott of the oil from both nations was put 
in place 
the oil executives said three modern sophisticated refineries 
in kuwait have been knocked out of the world market because of the 
boycott those refineries had a capacity of about 600000 barrels 
of refined oil per day some of which was arriving in the southern 
united states through the gulf of mexico the executives said 
the executives predicted that opec nations will not immediately 
increase production to make up for the iraqkuwait shortfall until 
they allow time for oil inventories to drop 
crude oil futures traded higher thursday as investors remained 
uncertain about what might happen in the middle east on the new 
york mercantile exchange the september contract for west texas 
intermediate rose 90 cents to 2736 a barrel 
retail gasoline prices shot up after the invasion and remain 
well above their levels of a month ago unleaded selfservice 
gasoline averaged 1216 a gallon nationally on monday compared 
with 1075 a gallon on aug 1 according to a spot check of 1400 
service stations by the american automobile association 
one of the oil executives called the current situation a 
longterm problem he predicted the price of crude would stay 
high as will the price of gasoline in coming months 
dozens of us refineries have closed in recent years when oil 
prices declined it would take a continued higher margin of profit 
on gasoline prices before oil companies build new refineries or 
increase the capacity of existing refineries he said 
