<TEXT>
exxon corp is fighting a 65 billion tax claim 
brought by the irs and the oil giant predicted it will chip away 
most of the governments case before going to trial next year 
this case when it gets to court is not going to be a 65 
billion case exxon tax lawyer william d obrien said thursday 
after filing a petition against the internal revenue service in 
us tax court in washington 
exxon chairman lawrence g rawl called the attempt by the 
government to collect almost three times the 25 billion that 
exxon has already paid in federal income tax for 198082 totally 
unwarranted 
after exxon announced its filing late thursday an irs spokesman 
in washington said no tax officials were immediately available to 
discuss the governments position in the decadeold dispute 
according to exxon the governments tax claim hinges on 
allegations that the oil giant avoided taxes by charging too little 
for oil it purchased from saudi arabia 
the irs completely ignores that saudi arabias policy of price 
moderation in the late 1970s and early 1980s required exxon to buy 
and sell saudi crude oil at the same prices established by the 
saudi arabian government obrien said at the time saudi arabia 
was trying to keep the price of oil under control by selling crude 
cheaply in the wake of the iranian revolution 
at the time the us government was also encouraging moderation 
in oil prices obrien said exxon finds it ironic that the 
government now has flipflopped during the latest oil crisis and 
started saying exxon should have charged more for its oil 10 years 
ago obrien said 
since exxons income tax filing is so complicated the company 
had waived the normal statute of limitations to give the irs plenty 
of time to complete its audits earlier this year exxon demanded 
that the irs move ahead on the matter giving the tax collectors 
little choice but to file a claim against the company obrien said 
exxon decided to force the irs hand because lawyers did not 
want to wait on the outcome of a similar fight between the 
government and texaco he said 
the governments contention that exxon did not charge enough for 
its oil much of which was distributed to the companys overseas 
subsidiaries involves 15 billion of the irs claim obrien 
described the other elements of the dispute as plainvanillatype 
items that ordinarily are in an oil companys tax return 
they include such items as deductions for drilling costs he 
said 
since exxon pushed the government into making its claim the irs 
employed a shotgun approach because it did not have time to 
thoroughly explore each item obrien predicted that negotiations 
between the two sides will result in many of the irs contentions 
being dropped 
should exxon end up paying more taxes the company has enough 
reserves on hand to avoid any effect on earnings obrien said he 
expects the case to go to trial before tax court judge meade 
whitaker sometime in 1991 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

