<TEXT>
the us trade deficit dropped to a sevenyear 
low of 507 billion in june the government said today but 
analysts expect it to resume acceleration once the impact of the 
middle east crisis takes effect on the price of oil imports 
the commerce department said the june deficit was down 347 
percent from the 777 billion imbalance posted in may it was the 
lowest deficit since 396 billion in june 1983 
until recently many economists and government officials 
including commerce secretary robert mosbacher were predicting that 
strong export growth would offset a growing dependence on foreign 
oil and result in the first us deficit below 100 billion since 
1983 
in fact the deficit for the first half of 1990 had been running 
at an annual rate of 9162 billion 
mosbacher welcomed todays news saying that while 
monthtomonth figures can be erratic the strong positive trend 
indicates increasing us export competitiveness in the world 
marketplace 
but some analysts question the effect of the iraqi invasion of 
kuwait and the subsequent rise in oil prices on later trade reports 
this month some say deficits could grow even larger once the 
higher oil prices are added to the import bill starting in august 
the stock market largely ignored the news and appeared to be 
concentrating on thursdays report on inflation and the mideast 
itself the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks dropped 3342 
points to 264802 by late morning 
the deficit improvement in june came from a 29 percent decrease 
in imports to 3937 billion and a 46 percent gain in exports to 
a record 343 billion the trade deficit is the difference between 
imports and exports 
a commerce spokesman said 500 million in airplane shipments 
contributed to the record exports 
it was the first time this year the deficit had dropped below 7 
billion it averaged 764 billion a month so far in 1990 compared 
to 912 billion in 1989 
but higher oil import costs now threaten to add even more than 
expected to the us import bill at the same time overseas 
economies have slowed lessening demand there for us goods 
so you have a combination of slower export growth and a higher 
oil import bill explained mark m zandi an economist with 
regional financial associates in bala cynwyd pa 
those two things are going to serve to limit any possibility 
of a significant improvement in the merchandise trade deficit over 
the next six months to a year he said 
oil imports in june fell 146 percent to 369 billion 
americans imported 840 million barrels a day down from 895 
billion in may the average price per barrel fell to 1464 down 
from 1557 
however in an ominous portent for trade reports this fall 
prices of the benchmark west texas crude had risen to 2736 by 
thursday 
in addition to aircraft other capital goods foods and 
consumer goods added to the export total 
on the import side there were declines in industrial supplies 
consumer goods and automobiles 
as usual the biggest deficit was with japan a 31 billion 
imbalance up from a 30 billion deficit in may 
the united states posted a surplus with western europe of 899 
million 
other deficits included taiwan 900 million china 800 
million canada 700 million brazil 300 million korea 200 
million and hong kong 100 million 
the deficit peaked at 15212 billion in 1987 and then dropped 
to 11853 billion the following year the 1989 deficit slid 
further to 109 billion 
a further improvement this year would have been good news for 
the bush administration which had counted on a strong trade 
performance to help keep the economy out of a recession and help 
reduce the federal budget deficit 
over the past three years fully onethird of overall us 
economic growth has been supplied by surging export sales that has 
become even more important recently as consumer spending has faded 
in the face of adverse economic news 
zandi noted that until the middle east developments the united 
states foreign oil bill totaled about 100 billion a year prices 
have soared since the invasion 
so if it remains at current levels it could add between 10 
billion and 15 billion over the coming year to our oil import 
bill he said 
at the same time evidence points to weaker exports because of 
slower economic growth particularly in japan and the pacific rim 
nations and to a lesser extent in western europe zandi said 
our forecast is for real export growth to slow to about 5 
percent over the next year from about 17 percent now he said 
zandi also had a scenario that would dramatically improve the 
deficit but one which few want to see 
if the economy slides into a significant recession where we 
see consumers and businesses retrenching that would cause the 
deficit to improve soley because imports would collapse he 
explained 
</TEXT>
