<TEXT>
venezuela on friday continued trying 
to persuade a majority of opec nations to meet to discuss oil 
production increases in wake of iraqs invasion of kuwait 
energy and mines minister celestino armas said venezuela was 
lobbying hard to get at least seven of the 13 organization of 
petroleum exporting countries to the table in order to work out an 
agreement to cover at least part of iraq and kuwaits 46 million 
barrels per day of blocked supply 
armas sent a letter dated friday to opec president sadek 
boussena calling for the meeting to decide on production increases 
continuing interruption of energy could seriously damage the 
longterm prospects of the petroleum industry for the producers as 
well as the consumers said the letter which was also sent to 
opecs secretary general in jiddah saudi arabia informed oil 
industry sources reported that venezuela the united arab emirates 
qatar and kuwait were responsive to a saudi call for an emergency 
session 
the sources who spoke on condition they not be named said a 
meeting may be convened either monday or tuesday in geneva 
they said iraq libya and ecuador were opposed to the proposal 
while indonesia has suggested a consultation rather than an 
emergency ministerial session 
algeria nigeria gabon and iran have not yet taken a stand 
they said iran in the past has sought to maximize prices 
iraqs oil minister on friday lashed out at the proposal for an 
emergency meeting insisting that the shortfall was created by the 
saudi blocking of iraqi oil exports from its transsaudi oil 
pipeline 
the staterun iraqi news agency quoted minister issam alchalabi 
as describing the call for the session as an attempt to add 
legitimacy to the justification of overproduction in violation 
of an opec agreement reached july 28 in geneva 
it was not immediately clear whether a small group or the cartel 
ministers would meet separately should the rest refuse to attend 
the proposed emergency meeting 
in venezuela armas indicated an agreement with several other 
opec nations was possible if attempts at full consensus fail 
this would be a formula to explore he said 
nor did he rule out a production increase by venezuela alone 
well cross that bridge when we come to it he said 
armas emphasized that venezuela had responsibilities to its 
clients among them the united states which buys about half of 
venezuelas 194 million barrel daily output and has asked 
venezuela to produce another 500000 barrels 
venezuela is responding to its hemispheric responsibilities 
armas said we have a responsibility to countries who are our 
friends 
he admitted that venezuela initially increased production after 
the united states had asked for more oil then changed its mind and 
turned off the taps 
he said venezuela at first had thought it a good idea to 
increase its inventories but changed its mind after realizing that 
this action could be misinterpreted by the market as a plan to 
unilaterally sell more oil armas said 
among other opec members saudi arabia has the potential to 
produce an estimated 1 million to 2 million barrels more a day and 
the uae about 500000 more 
