<TEXT>
the sudden rise in oil prices is jolting cities and states 
across the country already struggling with some of their worst 
budget woes in years 
restrictions on government travel have been ordered in indiana 
thermostats are being adjusted in government office buildings in 
baltimore and oil suppliers are being served notice in new york 
that price gougers will be remembered come contract time 
this is just another whammy along with the other cutbacks from 
the federal government weve received over the last 10 years j 
thomas cochran executive director of the washingtonbased us 
conference of mayors said in an interview friday 
one of the things we learned from the last oil crisis in the 
1970s was the tremendous amount of gasoline and fuel that cities 
use in their fleets and in government buildings this is definitely 
an item that will have an impact on their budgets he said 
actual service cuts have been slight just two weeks after the 
persian gulf crisis sent world oil prices soaring according to 
budget officials interviewed this week by the associated press 
what worries them most is the heightened prospect of a recession 
it could be a killer said rex olliff finance specialist 
for los angeles with a recession it would be difficult to get 
through this year and next year there would be a real problem 
sustained oil price increases of 25 percent to 30 percent would 
almost certainly bring about deep municipal and state service cuts 
other budget officials added 
virginia already struggling with its worst budget shortfall 
since world war ii 14 billion for 199092 faces 2 million in 
added costs if fuel prices remain where they are department of 
