navistar international corp said thursday its 
income for the third quarter dropped 786 percent to 6 million 
due largely to continuing weak demand for medium and heavy trucks 
the chicagobased truck maker which blamed a 77 percent drop in 
secondquarter earnings on slow sales said monday that it was 
suspending assembly operations in its springfield ohio and 
chatham ontario plants for five days to balance production with 
retail demand 
chatham operations will be suspended for an additional 10 days 
in september and springfields mediumtruck assembly line will be 
shut down for another five days in october the company said 
for the quarter ending july 31 navistar reported earnings of 6 
million on sales of 972 million compared to earnings of 28 
million on sales of 108 billion for the same 1989 period 
after dividends on the series g preferred stock income per 
common share broke even for the third quarter the company reported 
earnings of 8 cents per share for the 1989 period 
for the first nine months of fiscal 1990 navistar reported a 
net loss of 4 million or 10 cents per share on sales of 28 
billion compared to earnings of 100 million or 31 cents per 
share on sales of 32 billion during the 1989 period 
james c cotting chairman and chief executive officer of 
navistar said industrywide retail sales of medium and heavy trucks 
in north america were 74400 in the third quarter down 14 percent 
from the 86900 sold during the same period last year 
