cent lower to 117 cents higher with august at 4812 cents a pound 
in a report released after the close of trading the agriculture 
department said 7 million cattle were on us feedlots as of aug 
1 4 percent more than on that date a year ago 
the usda said july feedlot placements rose 18 percent over a 
year ago while july marketings off of feedlots rose 3 percent 
market analysts were most surprised by the placements figure 
which compared with expectations for about a 6 percent increase 
charles k levitt senior livestock analyst with shearson lehman 
hutton inc said the placements total of 15 million head was the 
third largest ever for july and 19 percent above the 10year 
avearge 
the july placements represent young cattle sold or moved to 
feedlots to be fattened on grain for slaughter in november and 
december 
levitt said feedlot operators aggressively sought animals in 
july because the feedlot business had been profitable that month 
and because feedgrain prices were declining suggesting the 
profitability would continue 
a bountiful winter wheat harvest in the southern plains where 
many feedlots are located contributed to a drop in wheat prices 
from about 330 to less than 3 a bushel in july making wheat an 
economical and readily available alternative to corn as a feed 
grain levitt said 
july placements also were higher than expected because good 
growing conditions had extended the usable life of the pastures on 
which young cattle are raised before they are moved to feedlots for 
finishing 
instead of moving animals to feedlots through the spring many 
producers kept their cattle on pastures until july when pasture 
conditions finally deteriorated levitt said 
