<TEXT>
the times publishing co on friday 
settled a complicated stock feud with texas billionaire robert m 
bass which according to company officials preserves independent 
control of the st petersburg times 
the bass group owns 40 percent of the voting stock but gets only 
57 percent of the dividends of times publishing co the 
partnership had wanted a better return on its investment and 
maintained directors had an obligation to recall preferred stock 
under the settlement the company will buy an undisclosed amount 
of common shares held by the bass group and will have the right to 
buy more shares from the partnership after three years 
times publishing will redeem or retire all of its nonvoting 
redeemable preferred stock as the partnership requested 
in return the bass group is dismissing its suit against the 
times it agreed not to comment beyond a threepage announcement 
andrew barnes chairman of times publishing said the 
agreement assures the longterm independence journalistic control 
and competitive vigor of the st petersburg times as well as 
significant ongoing support for the poynter institute 
the poynter institute controls a majority of the publishing 
companys stock and receives 83 percent of the dividends which are 
used to run the nonprofit journalism school in st petersburg 
david bonderman managing partner for the poynterjamison 
ventures ltd said he believes the settlement is in everyones 
best interest 
we always believed this to be a good investment and are happy 
we could work with andy barnes to help end a family dispute that 
has brewed for years he said 
the bass group gained a minority stake in the company in 
mid1988 the times publishing co owns the st petersburg times 
congressional quarterly and other magazines the st petersburg 
times is floridas secondlargest newspaper 
the feud between the sides focused on the companys stock 
dividends the bass group wanted to change the stock structure to 
get a better return on its investment while the times defended the 
arrangement as beneficial to the journalistic standards of the 
newspaper and the health of the poynter institute 
the bass group had made a 270 million buyout offer for the 
times publishing co but the directors rejected the offer earlier 
this year 
</TEXT>
