<TEXT>
nordstrom inc announced friday it settled all 
its outstanding claims with the national labor relations board but 
a union official demanded the company also admit wrongdoing 
the seattlebased retailer signed the agreement friday stating 
it would not punish employees for union activities or offer to 
employees benefits that are effective only if the union is ousted 
nordstrom spokesman dave marriott said 
nordstrom also will allow prounion employees the same 
privileges as antiunion workers in the matters of distributing 
handbills and posting fliers marriott said 
the settlement included a nonadmission of guilt clause 
which nlrb regional attorney walter mercer said is fairly common 
but united food and commercial workers local 1001 will object to 
any settlement unless nordstrom admits it has done what they have 
been accused of said union president joe peterson 
the union has five days to object after the settlement is 
signed mercer said 
terms of the settlement must be posted for 60 days in the five 
seattlearea stores and one tacoma store with ufcw local 367 and 
local 1001 employees mercer said 
overall 13 of the 19 charges filed by the ufcw have been 
dismissed or withdrawn said joe demarte nordstrom vice president 
for personnel 
the settlement wipes the slate clean in terms of the unfair 
labor practice charges that have been filed by the union demarte 
said 
he said the settlement was sought because we felt it was more 
important to reach a settlement of the issues pending before the 
nlrb rather than continuing to debate the merits of the unions 
allegations 
but peterson believed nordstrom wanted the settlement so that a 
new petition to decertify and oust the union could be circulated 
he said the process cannot begin while charges are pending before 
the nlrb 
the union is in the process of filing new charges against the 
retailer peterson said those charges will involve alleged 
discrimination against union negotiators at a store south of 
seattle peterson said 
the union also plans appeals on four other charges the labor 
board ruled against he said 
marriott said nordstrom expected such an action 
the ufcw represents about 1500 of nordstroms seattlearea 
employees nordstrom employs about 30000 people nationwide inn 60 
stores in six states 
in february the washington state department of labor and 
industries ruled that nordstrom had violated state law by failing 
to pay some employees for such activities as attending company 
meetings making deliveries and writing customer thankyou notes 
a union lawsuit seeks back pay for the workers 
